{
  "text": "Previous studies showed an individual's superior ability to adapt to artificial extensions of body dimensions while walking [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] or while judging whether an aperture is passable with the extensions [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . [CITATION_7] demonstrated that when rotation of the shoulders was free at the time of door crossing, participants were very successful in crossing a doorway while holding a 63-cm horizontal bar; virtually the same locomotor patterns as those during normal walking were observed.",
